the economic news last week was mostly positive but the word on 
inflation was worrying to many here is a brief recap 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in the second quarter the gross national product expanded at a 
31 percent annual pace down slightly from a revised 34 percent 
in the first three months of the year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
inflation as measured by a price index tied to the gnp climbed 
at a 47 percent annual pace in the second quarter the biggest 
advance since 1982 the index rose at a 35 percent rate in the 
first quarter 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
consumer spending in june rose a seasonally adjusted 10 percent 
to 321 trillion following a 06 percent increase in may it was 
the biggest increase since spending shot up 13 percent last august 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
americans personal income jumped 07 percent in june the best 
showing in three months the 279 billion increase to 404 
trillion followed a 05 percent rise in may 
the personal savings rate fell to 43 percent compared with 44 
percent in may the average savings rate for the first half of 
1988 41 percent is up substantially from 32 percent in 1987 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
import prices rose 27 percent in the apriljune quarter the 
biggest increase in more than a year 
the climb followed a 12 percent increase in the januarymarch 
period and was the steepest since the 41 percent jump in the first 
three months of 1987 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
major collective bargaining settlements in private industry 
during the first six months of this year provided for wage 
increases averaging 22 percent a year 
this was a slight decline from the 29 percent average wage 
increases in the contracts when they were negotiated two to three 
years ago 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
factory orders for durable goods advanced 88 percent in june 
their fastest pace in 30 months orders totaled 12523 billion 
1014 billion higher than the may total 
the june increase which followed a 19 percent decline in may 
was the biggest advance since an 89 percent jump in december 1985 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
foreign investment in the united states has jumped by more than 
215 percent since 1980 while american investment abroad increased 
by only onefifth that rate said a study by the congressional 
economic leadership institute 
the study said the pace is expected to accelerate with foreign 
buyouts in 1988 expected to make up as much as 20 percent of all 
us acquisitions up from 5 percent in 1987 but the report said 
foreign investments still account for only 5 percent to 6 percent 
of total us assets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the dow jones average of 30 industrials climbed 6774 points 
during the week finishing with a 4640point rise friday 
analysts attributed the advance to fresh strength in the dollar 
and favorable reaction to indications by chairman alan greenspan 
that the federal reserve has not changed credit policy recently 
