<TEXT>
new government statistics have revived the 
debate over whether the evil inflation monster which terrorized 
america during the 1970s is starting to awaken after having slept 
for most of this decade 
the reagan administration mindful of how voters perceptions 
will affect the presidential race insists there are no signs that 
inflation is becoming a problem but many private economists 
disagree 
these economists contend that the 68month economic expansion 
now the second longest of the postworld war ii period has used up 
all of the economys slack capacity 
tight labor markets and high factory operating rates are 
beginning to be translated into accelerating wage demands and 
higher prices they believe 
proponents of this theory received more ammunition last week 
with two new government reports one on wage increases and the 
other on overall economic growth and inflation 
the wage report showed that compensation for american workers 
wages and fringe benefits such as health insurance and pensions 
was rising this year at the highest rate since the summer of 1985 
wages and benefits which represent about twothirds of all 
business costs climbed by 45 percent in the 12month period 
ending in june compared with an increase of just 3 percent in the 
prior 12 months 
in a second report the government said an inflation index tied 
to the gross national product shot up at an annual rate of 47 
percent from april through june the fastest pace in almost six 
years the big jump in prices was blamed on higher consumer costs 
for food clothing and energy 
to the administration these reports were not cause for concern 
beryl sprinkel the presidents chief economic adviser blamed 
the inflation spurt on temporary factors including the drought and 
higher import costs because of the weaker dollar he insisted that 
there was no evidence that the economy was being overtaken by a new 
wageprice spiral 
we remain convinced that inflation will continue under 
restraint he told reporters during a briefing 
some private economists agree contending that inflationary 
pressures from the drought and tight labor markets are being offset 
by weakness in oil prices and a rebound in the dollar which 
reduces the costs of imports 
they note that the consumer price index after registering big 
jumps in the early spring calmed down in may and june only 03 
percent during the first six months of the year consumer prices 
rose 44 percent identical to the inflation rate for all of 1987 
i dont think we are seeing signs of higher inflation ahead 
said michael evans head of a washington consulting firm the 
rise in energy and clothing prices in the spring has since been 
reversed 
but this view is disputed by other private analysts who argue 
that inflation has once again become a threat for the first time 
since the early 1980s when the fight to reduce doubledigit 
inflation rates led to the steep 198182 recession 
the pickup in inflation is worrisome and is likely to continue 
through the end of the year raising the possibility of a slowdown 
in growth in 1989 said jerry jasinowski chief economist of the 
national association of manufacturers 
other analysts raise the possibility of an outright recession 
beginning next year the federal reserve since march has been 
taking a series of steps to push interest rates higher in an effort 
to ease inflationary pressures by dampening demand 
while this is the classic recipe for starting a recession 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan has maintained that a 
downturn can be avoided if the central bank acts quickly at the 
first sign of inflation when the amount of credit restraint needed 
is still small 
but david wyss an economist with data resources inc said the 
fed may have already waited too long 
the pattern is that the fed always waits too long to act then 
it clamps down too hard and causes a recession he said 
wyss said the fed has been hesitant about moving too quickly 
because this is a presidential election year and big interestrate 
boosts would not be viewed favorably by the administration in its 
efforts to keep the white house in republican hands 
as a result wyss predicted that consumer prices would rise at 
around 55 percent annual rate next year which would be the 
fastest inflation clip since an 89 percent rise in 1981 
alan sinai chief economist of the boston co said one of the 
problems is that demand pressures are outstripping the countrys 
ability to produce the goods and services 
we are starting to see a situation where we have too many 
dollars chasing too few goods he said once the economy runs 
out of slack we often get a credit crunch which ultimately leads 
to a recession 
