the grass is green and the crops are 
growing again in southern indiana thanks to rain that fell during 
the past two weeks the moisture has also given new life to the 
hopes of farmers 
everything was brown and then just in a couple of days it 
started greening and it looks like spring now said shirley 
heidrick who farms 750 acres in eastern owen county with her 
husband ron 
the worst drought in decades had dried out the couples fields 
but the recent rain improved chances that they will harvest enough 
corn and soybeans to make the loan payments on the spring planting 
mrs heidrick said 
were doing fine you know things are looking better and we 
just keep working she said 
southcentral indiana got more rain in july most of it in the 
third week than in may and june together the national weather 
service in indianapolis lists july rainfall of 388 inches may and 
june had 142 inches of rain 
milk production is up at jim elliotts owen county dairy farm 
where cows have more grass to eat and his oncedry pond again has 
water 
we just really dont know where we stand right now but it 
dont look near as bleak as it did before it started raining 
elliott said 
i had a lot of corn that was waisthigh before the rain and 
its headhigh now he said on my better soybeans they grew 
something like a footandahalf they were about kneehigh the 
taller ones now theyre up pretty near hiphigh 
janet hasler of southern greene county said the outlook is 
much brighter now than it was three weeks ago when her family 
planned to sell 20 sows and 100 baby feeder pigs because of a lack 
of feed corn 
the rain may have saved enough corn that the cuts wont have to 
be so drastic she said 
the first night it rained don stood outside and watched it 
rain he just stood out on our porch hasler said weve got 
green grass again and the weeds are growing and all of that good 
stuff theres lots of mudholes for the pigs to wallow in it looks 
like a normal summer now 
despite the increased rainfall farmers remain uncertain about 
how they will fare during the winter many face shortages of hay 
and corn to feed their livestock and sharply reduced crop income 
a purdue university agricultural expert says only 9 percent of 
indiana farmers have federal crop insurance 
