<DOCNO> AP880731-0083 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations economy kept growing in july 
although the pace slowed slightly from the previous month 
according to a survey of corporate purchasing managers 
the national association of purchasing management which 
conducts a monthly survey of economic trends at more than 250 
industrial companies said its index of economic growth dipped to 
59 percent in july from 593 percent in june 
a reading above 50 percent indicates the economy is expanding 
while levels below that point generally indicate the economy is 
contracting 
production growth slowed in july although new orders expanded 
sharply and inventories rose quickly the group stated 
the vigorous increase in new orders undoubtedly fueled by the 
surge in export orders is impressive and signals continued robust 
economic growth for the balance of the third quarter said robert 
j bretz chairman of the groups business survey committee 
among the purchasing managers surveyed 31 percent indicated 
their new orders had expanded compared with 34 percent in june 
while 12 percent said their rate of new orders was worse the same 
as in june 
of the 70 percent of the groups members that export 39 percent 
reported higher export orders during july up from 38 percent in 
june while only 3 percent said export orders were worse the same 
as in the previous month 
production slowed for 13 percent compared with 12 percent in 
june and increased for 25 percent down sharply from 35 percent in 
june 
inventories grew rapidly with 22 percent of the purchasing 
managers reporting higher inventories compared with 18 percent the 
previous month and 18 percent reporting a slowdown in inventory 
growth compared with 22 percent in june 
the group said that accounting for normal seasonal variations 
the rate of inventory increase was the greatest since july 1984 
some of the increase in inventory may be attributed to 
receiving products earlier than required from suppliers who closed 
their plants for vacation and maintenance and as a hedge against 
the significant number of price increases that went into effect 
july 1 the group stated 
in other areas 
prices rose for the 22nd consecutive month although the number 
of managers reporting higher prices declined some 63 percent 
reported higher prices compared with 66 percent in june while 2 
percent reported lower prices in both months 
employment rose for the second straight month after falling for 
three straight months nineteen percent of those surveyed indicated 
their employment rose compared with 20 percent the previous month 
while 12 percent indicated employment fell compared with 16 
percent in june 
vendor deliveries slowed in july a sign of economic growth 
that indicates demand for materials is outpacing manufacturers 
ability to fill orders some 21 percent indicated deliveries from 
their vendors had slowed compared with 32 percent in june 
the national association of purchasing management is a trade 
organization representing 30000 purchasing managers in 21 
industries 
</TEXT>
